sec.p:
Usually, the well-known working mechanism of ZABs is the oxidation–reduction reaction between zinc anode and air cathode during the discharge and charge process [27]. During the discharge process, oxygen diffuses to the air electrode, where it is reduced to hydroxyl ions under the action of an active catalyst. The hydroxyl ions generated on the air cathode migrate to the zinc anode through the separator, and then combine with zinc ions to form soluble zincate ion (Zn(OH)42−), when the zincate ion in the electrolyte reaches saturation, it will decompose to ZnO. In this process, the electrons released by the reaction between zinc and hydroxide are transferred to the air cathode through an external circuit, and the oxygen in the air in contact with the air cathode undergoes an ORR at the air cathode [58]. During the charging process, OER occurs at the air cathode, and the final reaction is the decomposition of ZnO into Zn and O2. The specific process is:Aircathode:O2+2H2O+4e-→4OH-\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
